%S A173726 1,2,4,7,10,16,21,30,34,53,55,77,87,110,118,162,165,210,220,275,286,
%T A173726 360,360,439,463,546,555,675,678,800,818,952,970,1132,1133,1311,1341,
%U A173726 1519,1530,1764,1772,2002,2028,2275,2299,2592,2590,2900,2939,3250,3265,3644
%N A173726 Number of reduced, normalized 3 X 3 semimagic squares with magic sum n.
%C A173726 In a semimagic square the row and column sums must all equal the magic sum. The symmetries are permutation of rows and columns and reflection in a diagonal. A "reduced" square has least entry 0. There is one normalized square for each symmetry class of reduced squares. See A173725 for a general normal form.
%C A173726 a(n) is given by a quasipolynomial of degree 3 and period 840. [corrected by _Hoang Xuan Thanh_, Jul 19 2026]
%D A173726 Matthias Beck and Thomas Zaslavsky, An enumerative geometry for magic and magilatin labellings, Annals of Combinatorics, 10 (2006), no. 4, pages 395-413. MR 2007m:05010. Zbl 1116.05071.
%H A173726 Thomas Zaslavsky, <a href="/A173726/b173726.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 12..10000</a>.
%H A173726 Matthias Beck, Thomas Zaslavsky, <a href="https://cs.uwaterloo.ca/journals/JIS/VOL13/Zaslavsky/sls.html">Six Little Squares and How Their Numbers Grow </a>, J. Int. Seq. 13 (2010), 10.6.2.
%H A173726 Matthias Beck and Thomas Zaslavsky, <a href="https://people.math.binghamton.edu/zaslav/Tpapers/SLSfiles/">"Six Little Squares and How their Numbers Grow" Web Site</a>: Maple worksheets and supporting documentation.
%H A173726 <a href="/index/Rec#order_31">Index entries for linear recurrences with constant coefficients</a>, signature (-2,-3,-3,-2,0,3,6,9,10,9,5,0,-6,-11,-14,-14,-11,-6,0,5,9,10,9,6,3,0,-2,-3,-3,-2,-1).
%F A173726 G.f.: x^12*(18*x^19 + 41*x^18 + 79*x^17 + 117*x^16 + 166*x^15 + 207*x^14 + 249*x^13 + 268*x^12 + 274*x^11 + 258*x^10 + 233*x^9 + 192*x^8 + 152*x^7 + 109*x^6 + 73*x^5 + 44*x^4 + 24*x^3 + 11*x^2 + 4*x + 1)/((1+x+x^2)*(1+x+x^2+x^3+x^4)*(1-x^4)*(1-x^6)*(1-x^7)*(1-x^8)). - _Hoang Xuan Thanh_, Jul 19 2026
%F A173726 a(n) ~ n^3/48. - _Charles R Greathouse IV_, May 26 2026
%F A173726 a(n) = (n^3-24*n^2+176*n-264)/48 + (n mod 2)*(n^2-21*n+55)/16 + ((2*n^2+1) mod 3)*(n-9)/3 + ((n^3+n^2+n+2) mod 4)*n/8 - [(n mod 4)=0]*7/2 - [(n mod 5)=0]*2 - [(n mod 6)=0]*2 - [(n mod 7)=0] - [(n mod 8)=0], where [] is the Iverson brackets. - _Hoang Xuan Thanh_, Jul 19 2026
%e A173726 a(12) is the first term because the values 0,...,8 make magic sum 12. a(12)=1 because there is only one normal form with values 0 to 8: (by rows) 0,4,8;5,6,1;7,2,3. a(13)=2 because the values 0,...,5,7,8,9 give two normal forms: 0,4,9;5,7,1;8,2,3 and 0,4,9;5,7,1;8,2,3.
%o A173726 (PARI) Vec(x^12*(1-x)^2*(18*x^19 + 41*x^18 + 79*x^17 + 117*x^16 + 166*x^15 + 207*x^14 + 249*x^13 + 268*x^12 + 274*x^11 + 258*x^10 + 233*x^9 + 192*x^8 + 152*x^7 + 109*x^6 + 73*x^5 + 44*x^4 + 24*x^3 + 11*x^2 + 4*x + 1)/prod(k=3,8,(1-x^k)) + O(x^60)) \\ _Hoang Xuan Thanh_, Jul 19 2026
